AGI - Donald Trump returns to attack Volodymyr Zelensky. >In a Miami intervention at the Future Investment Initiative (an investor convention), the US president defined Kiev's leader "a dictator who refuses to indict elections" and then added: "I love Ukraine, but Zelensky did a terrible job," &nbsp; "I am moving fast around the world to end wars, resolve conflicts and bring peace back to the planet. I want peace, I don't want to see everyone killed - Trump said. Look at the dead in the Middle East and those between Russia and Ukraine, but we will end this. There is no profit for anyone from having a Third World War, and we are not so far away, but I tell you there is no such risk. If the administration had remained" led by Joe Biden "for another year, you would have had the Third World War, but now it will not."
A few hours earlier on his social truth Trump had hit Zelensky by accusing him of "having done a bad job," not being able to bring peace to the region. Zelensky would better move fast or he won't stay a country anymore," wrote Trump labeling Zelensky as "a dictator". "His country is shattered and millions of people died unnecessarily" while the United States is "successfully denying the end of the war with Russia".&nbsp;
"Think - the president has still written -, a comedian of modest success> convinced the United States of America to spend 350 billion dollars to enter a war that could not be won, that it should never have started, but a war that he, without the United States and TRUMP, will never be able to solve".
"The United States has spent $200 billion more than Europe, > and Europe's money is guaranteed, while the United States will receive nothing in return. Besides that, Zelensky admits that half of the money we sent him is "dispersed". He refuses to call elections, he is very low in Ukrainian polls and the only thing he was good at was playing Biden as a violin." "A dictator without elections, Zelensky probably wants to maintain the 'cuccagna' train," concludes the post.
&nbsp;
<h2>Zelensky: "Trump lives in the space of Russian disinformation"</h2>
To unleash Trump's harsh response were the words of Zelensky, who attributed to Russia the responsibility of the positions of the President of the United States on the alleged lack of support for him by Ukrainian voters. "If anyone wanted to replace me now, this wouldn't work. Secondly, since 4% has been cited, we have seen this disinformation and we have understood that it comes from Russia.&nbsp; We understand and have proof that the United States and Russia are talking about these numbers," said Zelensky in statements from the Ukrainian state press agency Ukrinform. The Ukrainian president added, after observing that he had "great respect" for Trump "as leader of the American people", that the new tenant of the White House "lives in that disinformation space".
&nbsp;
<h2>Putin: "Positive interviews, I want to meet Trump"</h2>
Vladimir Putin evaluates "positively" talks in Riad between the American and Russian delegation. They took place in a "friendly" climate and the Russian president said "happy" of the prospect of meeting Donald Trump soon. "I haven't seen you in a long time. We have no close relationships," he said in an interview with Russian TV. "But in the four years he was president, we met and discussed our reports. I would be happy to meet him today, and I think he is, as evident from the nature of our telephone conversation."
Putin reported that during the Riad negotiations US representatives declared themselves available to cooperate. "On the American side there were completely different people (from those of the Biden administration, ndr) open to the negotiating process without any prejudice, without any condemnation of what was done in the past. There is openness to working together," Putin told reporters in an interview with the Russian TV channel 24.
According to the Russian president "there are no intermediaries in the dialogue between Russia and the United States". "Someone would like to be a mediator between Russia and the United States, but it's probably too much ambition," he said. "The goal and object of our talks at Riad were to restore Russian-American relations. The most important thing was to solve the most urgent issues, including the agreement on Ukraine. Without increasing the level of trust between Russia and the United States, it is simply impossible to solve many issues, including the Ukrainian crisis.
Putin also called "inappropriate hysteria" the Kiev protests for the absence of a Ukrainian delegation at the negotiating table between Russia and the United States. "Probably everyone has forgotten, but I remind you that exactly in a year, in February 2026, the Treaty of limitation of strategic weapons will expire. Do the representatives of Ukraine want to sit here at the negotiating table and act as mediators between Russia and the United States? Well, probably not."&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Moscow, &nbsp;recovered more than 800 km2 in the region of Kursk</h2>
General Serghei Rudskoi, number two of the Russian major state, said that his troops recovered "more than 800 square kilometers" in the Russian region of Kursk, partly controlled by Ukrainian troops following an offensive launched last August. "More than 800 square kilometers were released, or 64% of the territory initially occupied by the enemy (1.268 km2)", Rudskoi said, in an interview with the Russian military newspaper Krasnaya Zvezda. It is the first time that the Russian army publicly provides precise figures for the territories occupied by Ukraine in the Kursk region and admits that more than 400 km2 are still under control of Kiev. Ukraine claims to control 500 square kilometers in Kursk, a territory seen as a commodity of exchange in possible negotiations to end the conflict. The general added that in the Ukrainian regions of Donetsk, Zaporizhia and Kherson Russia controls "about 75% of the territory", while in the Ukrainian region of Lugansk, Kiev controls "less than one percent". Moscow had communicated the annexation of the four oblasts on September 30, 2022 while not having full control. In total, Russian forces conquered "almost 4,500 square kilometers" of Ukrainian territory from the beginning of the invasion at the end of 2024 and "more than 600 square kilometers" this year, said the general.&nbsp;

