AGI - A passenger train is derailed in Sri Lanka&nbsp; after colliding with a family of elephants crossing the tracks. The collision caused the death of 6 specimens, overwhelmed by the middle in the race that was traveling in the Habarana area, a natural reserve about 180 kilometers east of the capital, Colombo. The fight happened before dawn.
"The train is derailed, but there are no casualties among the passengers," said the local police, explaining how the only two surviving elephants were taken care of by the members of the reserve. The videos filmed after the accident, which had a strong echo on social media, show the extent of the impact, with animals lying, between blood pools, near the tracks..&nbsp;
Killing or wounding elephants is a criminal offence in Sri Lanka, which has about 7,000 wild elephants and where these huge mammals are considered a national treasure, partly because of their importance in Buddhist culture. For the authorities is &nbsp; the worst incident of this type recorded on the island. > In September 2018, in fact, two elephant puppies and their pregnant mother were killed in the same region in a similar collusion that involved, even in that case, a convoy in march.&nbsp; Since then, authorities have ordered train drivers to comply with speed limits to avoid hurting elephants when they are in areas where they are likely to cross the tracks.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
It is an easy time for the coexistence between elephants and men in Sri Lanka. Today's incident arrives a few days after the words of concern expressed by the government for the increasing number of clashes in some regions of the island. The peasants, desperate for the continuous looting and destruction of their crops, which often represent the only means of sustenance, &nbsp; they increasingly attack me. As stated on Sunday by Anton Jayakody, Deputy Minister of the Environment, in this feud 450 elephants and 150 people were killed only in 2023. The Minister said that the new government intends to end this problem by preventing elephants from crossing villages. "We plan to introduce several barriers - which could include electrical fences, trenches or other deterrents - to make it more difficult for wild elephants to venture into villages," Jayakod concluded.
&nbsp;

